@NODE "FUNCTION" "AmCEx: Function"
@NEXT "REQUIREMENTS"
@PREV "MAIN"
@TOC "MAIN"


  Function
  --------


  Converts international currency, using rates stored in a @{"local" LINK "TECHNICAL"} data
  file, which can be simply updated at any time by grabbing and saving an
  @{"html file" LINK "EXRATEUPD"} from a website.

  From v2.0 onwards, the @{"registered" LINK "SHAREWARE"} version of AmCEx comes with full
  @{fg shine}TCP support@{fg text} to make the update process easier.


  The program directory contains the program's own important data file
  @{"AmCEx.data" LINK "TECHNICAL"}, and the 'catalogs', 'help' and the 'flags' directories,
  which should be left where they are in the program directory.

  The latter contains all the flags for the countries listed on the
  particular pages, plus a couple of pattern images for use to fill the
  windows' backgrounds.




@ENDNODE

@NODE "REQUIREMENTS" "AmCEx: System requirements"
@NEXT "INSTALLATION"
@PREV "FUNCTION"
@TOC "MAIN"


  System Requirments
  ------------------


    Any Amiga running OS3.0+ and preferably a 256+ colour screen.



@ENDNODE

@NODE "INSTALLATION" "AmCEx: Installation"
@NEXT "USAGE"
@PREV "REQUIREMENTS"
@TOC "MAIN"


  Installation
  ------------


  Simply unarchive to ram: and drag its drawer to your harddrive.

  Due to possible changes in any new version of AmCurrency, compared to
  previous versions, it is advised to always delete any old version
  completely, before installing the new one.


  If you are using OS3.5+ then that's all.


  OS3.1 users, who don't get BOOPSI classes installed with the system,
  can use the string- and button.gadgets from the ClassAct2Demo.lha on
  Aminet.

  Using these, there is no input filter for floating point in the Amount
  entry, that one @{"only works" LINK "BUGS"} with string.gadget v45 or later.






@ENDNODE

@NODE "USAGE" "AmCEx: Usage"
@NEXT "MENUS"
@PREV "INSTALLATION"
@TOC "MAIN"


  Usage
  -----


  While the program is active, pressing the Help key at any time will
  display this page.  Since this guide runs asynchronously, the program
  can still be used while reading the guide.


  The text display below the Update gadget shows the 3-letter code of the
  selected, or active, base rate of whichever rates source is in use.
  The program does check if the from or to currencies, selected by the
  user, compares to one of these, and will adjust the calculation steps
  as necessary.


  To convert any currency, take the following steps:

    1) Highlight the currency of initial amount in the listview
    2) Click the 'From' gadget
    3) Type in the amount
    4) Highlight the currency of target money in the listview
    5) Click the 'To' gadget


  The actual calculation will take place whenever you enter, in any order
  you like, @{"the amount" LINK "BUGS"}, and/or select either of the two currencies for
  source and target.  AmCEx will recalculate the exchange even after the
  currency rates have been @{"updated" LINK "EXRATEUPD"}.


  Selecting the From and To currencies is now possible by using the
  cursor (arrow) keys:

    Up, Down:   This will cycle through the list entries

    Left:       Will set the From currency.

    Right:      Will set the To currency.





@ENDNODE

@NODE "MENUS" "AmCEx: Menus and menuitems"
@NEXT "EDITING"
@PREV "USAGE"
@TOC "MAIN"


  The menus and menu items
  ------------------------

                      RAmiga+   Description
   Project Menu:

     Enter             "m"      Activates Amount gadget, ready for entry

     Clear             "/"      Clears Amount and Target gadgets

     Rates             "r"      Update rates.  With valid keyfile present
                                this will access the web, otherwise the
                                specified file will be expected. There is
                                also a gadget for the same function.
     ---------------------
     Iconify           "i"      Self explanatory. See also new 'i' gadget
                                in the window, under the source-selector.

     Next Screen       "n"      Ditto.

     About             "?"      Gives program version and registered to.
     ---------------------
     Quit              "q"      Exit.  Will prompt when settings have
                                been changed.

   Edit Menu:

     DelEnt            "d"      Removes selected entry from list.

     AddEnt            "a"      Allows adding new entries from a list.

     EdtEnt            "e"      Edit/enter rates of selected entry.


   Misc Menu:

     Fixedwidth        "w"      Limits fontrequester to these fonts.
     ---------------------
     Load Font         "f"      Font requester.  Will resize the window,
                                depending on fontsize.

     Load Pattern      "p"      Filerequest for backfill pattern, will
                                close and reopen window.  To clear a
                                backfill pattern, select path, but no
                                file, and click Okay.

     Save Settings     "s"      Save all settings as icon tooltypes.

     Usage (HELP)      "h"      Starts localised AmCEx.guide





@ENDNODE

@NODE "EDITING" "AmCEx: Editing"
@NEXT "CUSTOMISING"
@PREV "MENUS"
@TOC "MAIN"


  Editing currency rates
  ----------------------

  The currency editor window displays the localised currency name, the
  3-character currency descriptorą, and the flag of the country where the
  currency is in use, to make the program look more colourful.

  All the currency base rates are shown on the right.  Each of these can
  be edited manually and all will be written to the AmCEx.data file when
  the 'Save' gadget is pressed.

  Updating currencies not found in either of the sources for daily rates
  can be done via the currency converter website:

    @{fg shine}http://www.xe.com/ucc/full.shtml@{fg text}


  The menu item 'Add List Entry' allows just that from a list which shows
  all known currencies.  Whether these will ever be supported with freely
  available rates, remains to be seen.


  The menu item 'Delete List Entry' will simply remove the highlighted
  currency entry from the listview.  Any thus removed currency will show
  up in the above list instead, so it can be added back any time.




  ą) Explanation:  @{fg fill}http://www.xe.com/iso4217.htm@{fg text}


@ENDNODE


@NODE "CUSTOMISING" "AmCEx: Customising the program"
@NEXT "EXRATEUPD"
@PREV "EDITING"
@TOC "MAIN"


  Customising the program
  -----------------------

  Look in the program icon's tooltypes.  All that can be defined is there
  in brackets, showing the defaults that the program will start up with,
  with a few exceptions.


  PUBSCREEN - Will be saved when you save the settings.


  FONTNAME  - No need to even write the '.font' at the end, though there
              is a provision to select it from the program.
  FONTSIZE  - This will influence the window size.


            Sidenote: The listview that shows the currencies, and the
                      window, as a direct result of this, will adjust
                      themselves to the length of any text that appears
                      within the listview.

  FIXEDWIDTHFONT - Is a switch and needs no parameters. Causes the font
                   requester to filter out proportional fonts.


  WINLEFT  \\
  WINTOP    -  The position of the window, including that of the zoomed
  ZOOMLEFT  -  state is automatically snapshotted, whenever the window is
  ZOOMTOP   -  moved. By default, it will appear centered on the screen.
  ICONLEFT  -  The same happens with the icon when iconified and moved.
  ICONTOP   -
  REQWIDTH  -  The width and position of the font and pattern requesters
  REQHEIGHT -  can also be fixed this way.
  REQLEFT   -
  REQTOP    -
  EDITLEFT  -
  EDITTOP   -  These refer to the 'Edit (and Add) Currency' windows.
  ADDLEFT   -
  ADDTOP   /

  DAYDATE - A '0' after this tooltype will display the Updated: date
            normally, anything else will change it, so that weekdays will
            be substituted, the same way as happens with the AmigaDOS
            datestamps.


  FRCURR -
  TOCURR - These two tooltypes will fix your preferred currencies so they
           are automatically selected when the program starts up.  This
           is best left to the program to set, using 'Save Settings', as
           the sorting sequence of the visible list doesn't coincide with
           the actual numbers, which are in the same order as the list on
           the webpage or in the data file.


  BACKFILL - allows to specify a background fill pattern for the window.
             The default is no backfill.  There is a filerequester that
             allows the selection of a suitable pattern for use.


  TEXTCOL - the pen with which the window text is drawn
  CURRCOL - the pen for the currency displayed under the flags
  TRGTCOL - the pen for the Target display colour
  DATECOL - the pen for the 'Updated:' date display
  BACKCOL - the background for the above

        For the above tooltypes the following colourpens are available
        on Workbench as standard (other values can be used too):

            DETAILPEN          or    0
            BLOCKPEN           or    1
            TEXTPEN            or    2
            SHINEPEN           or    3
            SHADOWPEN          or    4
            FILLPEN            or    5
            FILLTEXTPEN        or    6
            BACKGROUNDPEN      or    7
            HIGHLIGHTTEXTPEN   or    8
            BARDETAILPEN       or    9
            BARBLOCKPEN        or   10
            BARTRIMPEN         or   11


  FLAGSCALE - When this tooltype is set, only one set of flags will be
              used, and scaled down internally, depending on window size.
              If it is unset, two sets of flags are used.  If you do set
              this tooltype, you can delete the 'flagt' drawer, which
              contains the prescaled small flags.


  PREFERRED - Has no practical value, probably only sentimental or maybe
              patriotic reason to set it.  It applies only to the exrates
              source that has the five bases and allows to set the user's
              preferred base of these five.
              Default is GBP, and can be any of GBP, USD, EUR, DEM or JPY.




@ENDNODE



@NODE "EXRATEUPD" "AmCEx: Exchange rate updates"
@NEXT "TECHNICAL"
@PREV "CUSTOMISING"
@TOC "MAIN"


  Exchange rate updates
  ---------------------


  From v2.0 onwards, the @{"registered" LINK "SHAREWARE"} version of AmCEx can grab the
  rates by itself, provided it finds a TCP stack running, such as Miami
  or Genesis.  This means the user must be already online.


  In the unregistered version of v2.0+, the file first needs to be
  downloaded and saved as HTML from your browser:

  @{fg shine}http://www.moneyextra.com/rates/currency/tourist.htm@{fg text}


  So if you save "tourist.htm" to RAM: as per default, the program will
  find it easily and quickly, otherwise it will ask for a path.

  Both the tourist.htm and the subscription at "http://www.xe.com/"
  email file carry their 'updated' date within themselves.  The AmCEx
  parser will use that to stamp it upon the AmCEx.data file when saving,
  so that whenever the program loads this file, the date can be put into
  the 'Updated:' display in the window.  This date is also stored within
  the AmCEx.data file for each of the sources.


  The AmCEx.data file contains lines of the three-letter descriptors, the
  currency's name, and the exchange rate values for the bases.  These are
  then updated using the menu-item "Update Rates..." or the new 'Update'
  gadget in the window.  This will parse either of the html files and then
  build the @{"AmCEx.data" LINK "TECHNICAL"} file for offline usage.


  The radio buttons in the top left of the window select our source file
  of new rates, which we want to use to update our offline database.
  Naturally only those base rates are updated, which are present in the
  source file.


    0 - EXRATES:
    ratesfile = "ram:exrates.html"
    ratesurl  = "http://www.rate.co.uk/exrates.html" - sadly this one
                                    seems to be blocked for download.
    parsefor  = "Tourist Exchange Rates Here"
    bases     = 5

    1 - TOURIST:
    ratesfile = "ram:tourist.htm"
    ratesurl  = "http://www.moneyextra.com/rates/currency/tourist.htm"
    parsefor  = "a guide to what your Pound is worth."
    bases     = 1 - this has only UK Ł as a base for selling at moneyextra

    2 - EMAIL (by subscription at "http://www.xe.com/")
    ratesfile = "ram:text"
    ratesurl  = Can not be accessed via the web.
    parsefor  = "Rates as of "
    bases     = 2 - base currency can be anything, xxx/unit & units/xxx




@ENDNODE


@NODE "TECHNICAL" "AmCEx: Technical information"
@NEXT "PROGUPDATES"
@PREV "EXRATEUPD"
@TOC "MAIN"


  Technical information
  ---------------------


  Added the subscription based email service as a new source while the
  previously used source was dropped due to unavailability.

        @{fg fill}http://www.xe.net/cus/sample.htm@{fg text}


  Although the lists will show up in the localized language, any parsing
  is done using the 3-letter currency descriptors.

  The flags are saved using these three letter descriptors, so by simply
  adding a .gif extension to make up a filename, the graphic file can be
  easily loaded, corresponding to any of the currencies.

  Currency strings can be up to 62 characters in length.

  The .data file starts with the word 'AExBases;' followed by all the
  currency descriptions and the headers from the email-updates, all on
  the same line. Then follow the digits for denoting the currency used
  for the base rate, the rates source file selector and the number of
  bases used in that file.  This first line is terminated by the three
  dates, one for each of the rates sources.

  From line two onwards live all the currencies, line by line, they are
  sorted by the three letter descriptor. All fields in the data file are
  delimited by a semicolon ';', including the ends of the lines. The
  program, when it reads through the file, pokes 0s in those positions,
  to make them into C strings, easy to pick up.

  The 'y' or 'n' at the end of the currency lines signifies whether the
  currency has been added to the visible currencies list or not.

  There are two different .data files in the archive:

    AmCEx.data      - a working .data file from everyday use.
    AmCEx_000.data  - all currency rates are zeroed.





@ENDNODE


